WEBVTT

00:00.706 --> 00:02.749
Hey Bridgestown family, Bethany here.

00:03.289 --> 00:12.481
I wanted to take a moment to invite you to Bridgestown's eighth annual Holy Spirit Conference on January 23rd and 24th at Portland's Keller Auditorium.

00:13.303 --> 00:16.687
The theme of this year's conference is the healing after the healing.

00:17.168 --> 00:25.138
And we'll be exploring how the miraculous work of the Holy Spirit is often just the first step to deeper, slower soul level healing.

00:25.698 --> 00:37.396
Like the man-born blind in John 9, every part of us that God heals only exposes a deeper part of us awaiting healing from the same God, and the deepest healing is often the slowest kind.

00:38.398 --> 00:44.908
We are so excited to be joined by contributors like Ruth Haley Barton, Kurt Thompson, Ken Chigamatsu, and Brooke Legitwood.

00:45.729 --> 00:49.495
Livestream tickets are available now at HolySpiritCode.me.

00:50.296 --> 00:51.538
I hope you can join us.

01:03.970 --> 01:08.116
Our passages are out of Luke in chapter 10 and chapter 18.

01:09.257 --> 01:11.260
Chapter 10 starting in verse 25.

01:11.300 --> 01:15.586
On one occasion, an expert in the law stood up to test Jesus.

01:16.106 --> 01:19.030
Teacher, he asked, what must I do to inherit eternal life?

01:19.871 --> 01:20.813
What is written in the law?

01:20.993 --> 01:22.675
He replied, how do you read it?

01:23.316 --> 01:29.344
He answered, love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your strength, and with all your mind, and love your neighbor as yourself.

01:30.005 --> 01:33.810
You have answered correctly, Jesus replied, do this, and you will live.

01:34.274 --> 01:38.038
But he wanted to justify himself, so he asked Jesus, and who was my neighbor?

01:38.839 --> 01:44.425
In reply, Jesus said, a man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho when he was attacked by robbers.

01:44.825 --> 01:48.850
They stripped him of his clothes, beat him, and went away leaving him half dead.

01:49.450 --> 01:54.516
A priest happened to be going down the same road, and when he saw the man, he passed by on the other side.

01:55.236 --> 01:59.962
So to a Levite, when he came to the place and saw him, passed by on the other side.

02:00.562 --> 02:04.146
But a Samaritan, as he traveled, came where the man was.

02:04.322 --> 02:06.085
And when he saw him, he took pity on him.

02:06.646 --> 02:10.431
He went to him and bandaged his wounds, pouring on oil and wine.

02:11.153 --> 02:15.519
Then he put the man on his own donkey, brought him to an inn, and took care of him.

02:16.160 --> 02:19.465
The next day, he took out to Daenerai, and gave them to the innkeeper.

02:19.886 --> 02:20.968
Look after him, he said.

02:21.529 --> 02:25.395
And when I return, I will reimburse you for any extra expense you may have.

02:26.316 --> 02:30.382
Which of these three do you think was a neighbor to the man who fell into the hand of robbers?

02:31.244 --> 02:32.786
The expert in the law replied,

02:33.026 --> 02:34.649
the one who had mercy on him.

02:35.350 --> 02:37.554
Jesus told him, go and do likewise.

02:38.816 --> 02:40.860
Enough lip a couple pages to Luke 18.

02:43.384 --> 02:49.334
To some who were confident of their own righteousness and looked down on everyone else, Jesus told this parable.

02:50.196 --> 02:54.684
Two men went up to the temple to pray, one a Pharisee and the other a tax collector.

02:55.244 --> 02:56.146
The Pharisee

02:56.546 --> 03:08.298
stood by himself and prayed, God, I thank you that I'm not like other people, robbers, evil doers, adulterers, or even like this tax collector, I fast twice a week and give a tenth of all I get.

03:09.119 --> 03:11.621
But the tax collector stood at a distance.

03:11.641 --> 03:18.508
He would not even look up to heaven, but beat his breast and said, God, have mercy on me, a sinner.

03:19.769 --> 03:24.594
I tell you that this man, rather than the other, went home justified before God,

03:25.186 --> 03:31.556
for all those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted."

03:32.357 --> 03:33.299
This is the word of the Lord.

03:33.980 --> 03:34.781
Thanks be to God.

03:38.427 --> 03:43.355
Several years ago, I was at the swimming pool on the first day of vacation.

03:44.316 --> 03:48.242
I was coming off a particularly hectic season at work.

03:48.343 --> 03:51.608
I'd said far too many yeses, and I'd got it all done.

03:51.768 --> 03:53.010
I'd pulled it off.

03:53.666 --> 03:56.709
but the collateral of all that was still living within me.

03:56.829 --> 04:10.444
So I was overtired and emotionally drained and spiritually depleted, not my best self by any stretch of the imagination which everyone around me knew but I wasn't aware of, not quite yet.

04:12.326 --> 04:19.954
That's the state I was in when I was there at the swimming pool on the first day of vacation and to make a very embarrassing story somewhat bearable.

04:20.834 --> 04:30.484
I was getting all huffy and puffy because Kirsten, who had packed a picnic lunch for us to have at the pool, had forgotten my plastic fork.

04:31.185 --> 04:37.091
Now, I wasn't flying off the handle or anything ridiculous like that, but I was irritated, like I was tense.

04:37.471 --> 04:41.796
And tension has this way of just owning the atmosphere that it's in.

04:42.357 --> 04:47.602
Sucking all of the air out of every environment that it occupies, doesn't it?

04:47.746 --> 04:58.160
I'm sitting there on the edge of a public pool with my feet dangling in the water where my kids are happily playing and my wife is enjoying them and I'm infecting the air with this kind of tense agitation.

04:58.200 --> 05:02.525
And it was then that Kirsten said something truly loving to me.

05:04.328 --> 05:08.493
Tyler, I love you and I will always love you.

05:10.596 --> 05:15.122
But I don't particularly like being around who you've most recently become.

05:17.154 --> 05:23.582
It's rare for someone whose profession is talking to be left speechless, but that's what I was.

05:23.643 --> 05:36.519
Not offended speechless, more like sobered, because when she said it, I realized something that I'm not sure I like being around who I'd most recently become.

05:37.861 --> 05:41.586
You see, somewhere along the way and all those well-intentioned yeses,

05:41.986 --> 05:45.892
I had lost my laughter and my playfulness and my ease.

05:45.912 --> 06:04.920
I was a man on a mission, and that's good company if you're up for the intensity of a mission, but not such good company if you're just trying to play Marco Polo at the pool with a five-year-old or read a few pages of a novel before you turn in and either stay up a little bit too late watching one more episode of Shrinking.

06:06.222 --> 06:11.410
Somewhere along the way, with the very best of intentions, I had lost my playfulness.

06:11.938 --> 06:18.427
my ease, my silliness, and I'd started taking myself way too seriously.

06:19.408 --> 06:32.626
And then the person in my life who knows me best and loves me most interrupted me in the midst of a plastic fork-driven poolside pout to very kindly but honestly hold a mirror up to me and show me who I'd become.

06:34.114 --> 06:36.537
So we're picking up on our teaching series of prayer-shaped life.

06:36.578 --> 06:43.748
Next Sunday, we're going to be joined by Faith Yuri Cho, who's going to lead us into the practice of ordering our days around friendship with God.

06:43.788 --> 06:52.280
But first, up to this point, we have covered being with Jesus through the practice of silent prayer, becoming like Jesus through the practice of singing our prayers.

06:52.300 --> 06:59.090
And up for today is doing what Jesus did through the practice of incarnated prayer.

06:59.490 --> 07:08.445
Now, incarnated prayer is the practice of letting Jesus lead me where I do not want to go to become who I want to be.

07:09.167 --> 07:13.514
That's going to make sense after we take a long walk with Jesus.

07:14.195 --> 07:22.770
Near the end of Luke chapter 9, we read, as the time approached for him to be taken up into heaven, Jesus resolutely set out for Jerusalem.

07:22.946 --> 07:35.123
And what follows is this 10 chapter section of Luke's gospel, which is framed entirely as the walk from Galilee to Jerusalem, which passes through Samaria along the way.

07:35.643 --> 07:40.831
A long walk where Jesus tells a whole bunch of stories or what we normally call parables.

07:41.211 --> 07:48.801
And every last parable in this 10 chapter section of Luke is entirely unique to Luke's gospel.

07:49.703 --> 07:50.464
So check this out.

07:51.525 --> 07:52.146
Luke,

07:52.674 --> 08:03.017
records 10 stories Jesus told that Matthew, Mark, and John left out, all of them happening on this one long walk.

08:04.420 --> 08:12.658
Jesus is walking to Jerusalem to die, and he is passing the time on this long road trip.

08:13.090 --> 08:15.174
by telling stories to his disciples.

08:15.615 --> 08:22.568
And we read two of those stories just a moment ago, one from the very beginning of this journey, and one from near the very end.

08:22.668 --> 08:36.594
Two stories that reveal something essential about how prayer, which masquerades as the spiritual practice of retreating from the world, is in fact the essential spiritual practice that forms to send to people who do what Jesus did in the world.

08:37.346 --> 08:45.116
Now the Good Samaritan is the first story that we read, and it's the most broadly well known of the stories Jesus tells in Luke's walk.

08:45.837 --> 08:55.971
Walking the road from Jerusalem to Jericho, a notoriously dangerous route back in Jesus' day due to high crime, a man was mugged, left robbed, and bleeding on the sidewalk.

08:56.572 --> 09:01.298
Then a priest walks by and passes on the other side of the street.

09:01.666 --> 09:10.656
After that, a Levite comes along, which is a particular type of priest, and he sees him, but he pretends not to, and just passes by and gets along with his day.

09:11.777 --> 09:18.665
In the world of psychology, there's mounting evidence that human beings are pre-wired to respond to one another's suffering.

09:19.265 --> 09:27.154
That from birth, an infant, when they hear the crying of another infant will respond automatically with their own cries.

09:27.855 --> 09:30.578
A baby who is perfectly contented at peace,

09:30.850 --> 09:36.317
If they hear another baby crying, they will attempt to share in their distress in some way.

09:36.817 --> 09:48.552
And in fact, as early as 14 months, a baby who hears the crying of another infant will actually attempt to actively intervene, to alleviate whatever is bothering them.

09:49.193 --> 09:59.986
Meaning that to see a human being in distress and pass by, like the priest in Levi, who do so to the man on the Samaritan road, or like you and I might do,

10:00.322 --> 10:10.518
when we see someone distressing the need on the street side in Portland, that's not just evidence of a lack of spiritual formation, theologically speaking.

10:11.139 --> 10:23.858
It's actually evidence of human deformation, psychologically speaking, the loss of something inherent to your humanity to some degree or another.

10:24.418 --> 10:30.367
Next is Samaritan, the ethnic less thans of Israel, who were thought to be spiritually misguided to put it very politely.

10:30.948 --> 10:33.072
Next is Samaritan walked by, verse 33.

10:34.153 --> 10:40.504
But a Samaritan, as he traveled, came to where the man was, and when he saw him, he took pity on him.

10:41.084 --> 10:44.610
Now, the English word pity is the Greek spunkizo mind.

10:44.630 --> 10:49.618
It's almost always translated compassion in the New Testament.

10:49.698 --> 10:52.041
So this American doesn't make a single stop here.

10:52.121 --> 10:59.990
He enters into this man's pain for a moment, and then he pays for his healing and rehabilitation very slowly over time.

11:00.050 --> 11:13.586
And we know that he comes back to visit the man, remaining in relationship over time, not a transactional moment, but rather a kinship relationship of mutual love born from noticing and entering into a need in the moment.

11:13.666 --> 11:26.507
The priest and Levite in the story, who saw need in a person but chose their convenience over compassion, they're suffering from what we commonly refer to as compassion fatigue.

11:28.750 --> 11:31.615
Russia launched new deadly air attacks across Ukraine.

11:32.757 --> 11:38.706
A multi-vehicle crash in Uganda involving buses and the lorry killed over 40 people.

11:39.490 --> 11:45.640
A recent heist at the Louvre in Paris revealed holes in security in the museum director slated to testify in court.

11:46.581 --> 11:55.436
Virginia Joffrey published a memoir detailing her accusations of sexual exploitation and abuse against Prince Andrew and Jeffrey Epstein.

11:56.057 --> 12:00.664
Mosquitoes were found in Iceland for the first time, possibly due to record heat.

12:01.305 --> 12:06.674
Those are the top global headlines in the news from the last seven days.

12:07.330 --> 12:12.335
The powerless are being violently attacked by the powerful people riding the bus to work.

12:12.675 --> 12:16.479
Kids on their way to school just had their lives snatched from them in an instant.

12:16.919 --> 12:20.302
Precious art is being stolen in a real life oceans 11.

12:20.803 --> 12:24.847
Women are being exploited and stripped of their dignity by men of privilege and status.

12:25.367 --> 12:28.410
Oh, and there's a pretty strong chance the whole earth is melting.

12:30.512 --> 12:36.818
Compassion fatigue is a condition born from constant interaction with human suffering

12:37.538 --> 12:43.727
that is too big, too far, and too complex for me to enter into in any meaningful way.

12:45.550 --> 12:56.687
Every last one of the headlines I just read you is a story about pain, headlines about suffering that's too far away, too complex to untangle, too big for me to carry on my shoulders.

12:56.707 --> 12:57.668
So then what do I do?

12:59.591 --> 13:04.078
You can let the needs of the world direct your attention to the needs of your world.

13:05.180 --> 13:06.802
That's where you can start at least.

13:07.586 --> 13:12.011
Compassion, that's the word Jesus uses to set the Samaritan apart in his story.

13:12.612 --> 13:20.522
In our English word, compassion, if we trace it to its biblical roots, it comes from the Hebrew term Raham, which literally means to co-suffer.

13:20.902 --> 13:25.628
It's linguistically tied to the Hebrew word for womb, as in a mother's womb.

13:25.668 --> 13:28.291
The two are very closely related all throughout the Bible.

13:28.732 --> 13:37.042
So according to the unfolding story of God, compassion is to take the needs of another and then carry them within myself.

13:37.858 --> 13:39.901
for your burden to become my burden.

13:39.941 --> 13:47.234
You're weeping, my weeping, you're hurting, my hurting, you're hungry, my hunger, your need, my need.

13:47.855 --> 13:53.564
But compassion isn't just to take the pain of another person and carry it within myself and keep it there.

13:53.604 --> 13:54.706
That's called empathy.

13:55.234 --> 13:56.696
feeling what you feel.

13:57.157 --> 14:10.779
Compassion is to feel what you feel in a regenerative sort of way that allows me to actually give birth to some form of new life in the world after I've carried your need for a time.

14:12.101 --> 14:22.738
On the very heels of this story, Jesus tells another story, one that's joined to this one, illustrating prayer as borrowing bread from a neighbor to feed the people who happen to be under my roof tonight.

14:23.234 --> 14:29.844
So prayer sends me out doing what Jesus did as far as the complete stranger by the roadside.

14:30.204 --> 14:38.577
And prayer sends me doing what Jesus did as close as the common company in my home as I reach for bread to offer them.

14:39.278 --> 14:47.410
The environment that I do what Jesus did isn't only in good Samaritan type chance encounters with strangers who become neighbors.

14:47.990 --> 14:53.138
It's equally, in fact, maybe even mostly among people under my roof,

14:53.442 --> 14:58.009
in my family, as common as my friendships in my local community.

14:58.850 --> 15:03.177
The prayer principle that Jesus teaches in the Good Samaritan story goes like this.

15:03.758 --> 15:08.364
Devotion to prayer is inseparable from devotion to others.

15:09.827 --> 15:20.082
Prayer is both the place I cultivate intimate relationship with God and then from that foundation, prayer becomes the foundation for all of my other relationships.

15:20.482 --> 15:28.477
for the way that I relate to and think about myself, the way that I interact with others, the way that I relate to family, friends, strangers, and neighbors alike.

15:28.497 --> 15:35.250
If you know prayer merely as a ritual of escape, then you can revel all you want in the promises of God.

15:36.194 --> 15:39.959
You can juggle the blessings He's given you in prayerful gratitude.

15:40.000 --> 15:51.356
You can invite Jesus to shoulder the burden of your weekly anxiety, to deliver you from your pain, to forgive you for your wrongs, but you will never see the battered one by the roadside through prayerful eyes.

15:52.538 --> 16:03.634
You will walk by whispering prayers for the plenty that God has given you entirely unaware that He has given you too much, also you'd have enough to share.

16:04.610 --> 16:06.552
Prayer's not a ritual of escape.

16:07.613 --> 16:12.299
It's a ritual of invasion on earth as it is in heaven.

16:12.319 --> 16:13.881
That's how Jesus taught us to pray.

16:14.742 --> 16:24.853
He taught us to pray with our eyes open to the needs of our neighbors, to pray with our ears and our lips first, absolutely, but the prayer that gets spoken is meant to become lived.

16:24.913 --> 16:32.722
If we don't live the prayers that we speak, our prayers are revealed as hollow, fraudulent, counterfeit,

16:33.794 --> 16:38.080
So how do I know if I'm praying like Jesus and not like the priest and Levite in this story?

16:38.921 --> 16:45.411
How do I know if my prayer is the kind that pulls heaven down to earth and me and then spreads it over God's creation?

16:45.892 --> 16:52.501
Or if for me, prayer is just a ritual of escape where I ask God to sponsor my plans and bless my preferences.

16:53.182 --> 16:54.364
Here's an easy metric.

16:55.686 --> 17:01.234
Does this prayer move me closer to another person in sacrificial love?

17:03.842 --> 17:14.575
Praying in the will of God is the kind of prayer for another person that starts on my lips in seclusion and then moves my hands and feet to embody, to incarnate that prayer in active love for others.

17:15.116 --> 17:16.077
So how do I know it?

17:16.197 --> 17:25.849
If I'm using prayer as a self-serving ritual of escape, or if I'm using prayer as a selfless practice of formation, oh, that's easy.

17:26.550 --> 17:32.978
Just be honest with yourself, is my prayer moving me closer to the needs of my neighbors?

17:35.202 --> 17:45.383
Christian writer Evelyn Underhill says, it is useless to utter fervent petitions for the kingdom to be established and that God's will be done unless we are willing to do something about it ourselves.

17:45.984 --> 17:54.962
Healthy expansion of the spiritual life depends on the balance struck between two movements, the direction of the soul's love and energy towards God and then towards other men.

17:55.618 --> 18:05.071
Clinical psychologist and Jesus follower James Finley says, our union with others is essential to our union with God, and our union with God is essential to our union with others.

18:05.252 --> 18:08.296
Each one properly pursued leads to the other.

18:08.316 --> 18:16.527
Travis Monctomis Burton, we receive from God in the spirit, and in the same spirit, we return our love to God through our brothers.

18:17.148 --> 18:24.018
And Henry Nowhan writes, a growing intimacy with God deepens our sense of responsibility for others.

18:24.738 --> 18:39.154
Every church tradition and every monastic order in history has been built between striking the balance between two sets of spiritual practices, prayer and work, being with God and being with others.

18:40.956 --> 18:49.726
Asking him to redeem my inner being by his spirit and then partnering with the same spirit and renewing all of creation.

18:50.607 --> 18:53.330
Prayer shapes us over time.

18:53.474 --> 18:56.598
into people of increasing Christ-like compassion.

18:57.118 --> 19:03.366
And that doesn't mean compassion fatigue, where we are paralyzed by the pain of the world.

19:04.167 --> 19:12.797
But neither does it mean compassion overload, where we take personal responsibility for everyone else's pain around us.

19:13.558 --> 19:19.986
Jesus lived his prayers compassionately, but Jesus also only did what he saw the Father doing.

19:20.386 --> 19:24.350
So then how do I know, how do I know where my prayers are sending me?

19:24.370 --> 19:30.496
How do I live, not by compassion, fatigue or compassion overload, but by prayerful compassion?

19:31.457 --> 19:42.228
Well, I would say this, just prayerfully sit with God over time, evaluating where do my resources and my neighbors need overlap?

19:43.849 --> 19:48.594
Like what is God entrusted to you, materially and immaterialally?

19:49.826 --> 20:09.211
And sure, all the things that you concretely have that you could share, but in addition to that, the gifts and talents that you possess, the opportunities and limitations of your life stage at present, the construction of your family, the home that you live in, the personality structure that you have, what has God given to you?

20:09.251 --> 20:14.898
And where does that overlap with today's needs?

20:15.330 --> 20:18.153
in the neighbors around you, right in that overlap.

20:18.213 --> 20:21.216
That's where prayerful compassion comes alive.

20:21.336 --> 20:43.378
That's how we live in the context of our city and in our ordinary lives by the spiritual rhythm that is grounded Jesus' apprentices from the very beginning prayer and work with God, with others, redeeming my soul, renewing the world, love of the Father poured it in, love for neighbor poured out in heaven,

20:43.490 --> 20:44.251
on earth.

20:44.351 --> 20:50.500
This is the breath of the spiritual life in heaven, on earth.

20:50.520 --> 20:56.968
I inhale through prayer and I exhale as I incarnate those prayers.

20:58.711 --> 21:02.756
Have you ever noticed that prayer isn't included in the biblical list of spiritual gifts?

21:04.879 --> 21:06.942
Seems like a massive oversight, doesn't it?

21:08.304 --> 21:12.850
We're told that God gifts people to be particularly effective and

21:12.962 --> 21:23.877
sharing their faith with Jesus with another, to teach, to organize an order, to prophesy, to heal, to show mercy and the list goes on, but never once that God gives people to pray.

21:23.917 --> 21:29.184
And you probably know some people who seem particularly gifted in prayer, don't you?

21:29.244 --> 21:32.688
Or at least more committed to it than most everybody else.

21:34.231 --> 21:36.454
It certainly seems like Paul forgot one of the gifts.

21:37.895 --> 21:42.802
Unless, unless prayer is the breath of the Spirit,

21:43.554 --> 21:44.856
not a gift of the Spirit.

21:45.937 --> 21:48.400
Because no one's gifted to breathe, breath is just life.

21:49.080 --> 21:51.483
It's what fuels every gift and talent you possess.

21:51.543 --> 21:53.866
Without breath, everything else stops.

21:54.206 --> 21:55.248
And that's what prayer is.

21:56.109 --> 21:57.750
It's the breath of the spiritual life.

21:58.291 --> 22:05.439
It is the source that gives life and vitality to every expression of the Spirit within every person who calls Jesus Lord.

22:05.740 --> 22:08.563
And breathing involves exhaling.

22:09.644 --> 22:11.186
Every bit as much as inhaling.

22:13.154 --> 22:17.220
I just want to stop for just a second before we move on from here.

22:19.283 --> 22:23.989
Who in this room is being addressed by the Spirit of God?

22:26.292 --> 22:34.444
Who in this room, just as I've been talking, is being moved toward a hands and feet incarnated kind of prayer?

22:36.046 --> 22:38.429
Do you feel a desire waking up in you?

22:39.371 --> 22:41.874
Do you feel invited, compelled,

22:42.050 --> 22:47.877
called to a life of inhaling and exhaling through prayer.

22:48.859 --> 23:05.560
To find yourself in the days ahead, going where your prayers lead you, living in moments that first started in a prayerful imagination, having friendships that are so unlikely the only explanation is the compassion born in prayer.

23:06.781 --> 23:10.546
If you do, then look, if you feel that desire waking up in you,

23:11.170 --> 23:17.961
If you feel like you're doing more than listening to a sermon, but being awoken by the Spirit of the Living God, I want to ask you to do something.

23:18.001 --> 23:22.428
It's going to take some boldness, but it's not going to take nearly as much boldness as actually living your prayers.

23:23.089 --> 23:30.962
I just want to invite you to wherever you are to stand right now, because I'd simply love to pray for you before we continue on with the teaching.

23:42.018 --> 23:49.127
Spirit of the living God, you are our helper, our comforter, our counselor.

23:49.948 --> 24:07.710
And I pray in Jesus' name that you would be the helper of my brothers and sisters in the days ahead and that you would walk them right into moments they're standing in that started in the hidden place of quiet prayer just between you and them.

24:08.311 --> 24:10.514
In Jesus' name, amen.

24:12.162 --> 24:13.966
All right, let's move to our second story.

24:14.708 --> 24:19.238
In this one, Jesus is describing two different people who are praying side by side.

24:20.341 --> 24:24.370
One of them is a Pharisee, meaning he is

24:24.802 --> 24:27.767
one of the most outwardly devout priests of his day.

24:27.847 --> 24:32.954
The other is a tax collector, meaning he is one of the most outwardly unethical people of his day.

24:33.415 --> 24:37.221
He had accumulated all of his wealth by partnering with the oppressor.

24:37.702 --> 24:43.931
Only in Jesus' story, the Pharisee prays in a way that keeps God at a distance.

24:43.951 --> 24:50.962
He touts his own spiritual scorecard but doesn't allow God to confront him with his own ongoing need for formation.

24:51.042 --> 24:57.893
The tax collector on the other hand has a much less impressive spiritual scorecard, but allows God to confront him.

24:58.634 --> 25:02.560
And that confrontation with God leads him to greater spiritual depth.

25:02.580 --> 25:05.164
And that Jesus says is righteousness.

25:06.006 --> 25:09.852
It is the willingness to allow yourself to be confronted by the spirit of God.

25:10.653 --> 25:16.402
And then that confrontation be the inciting incident guiding you into greater depth.

25:17.282 --> 25:22.428
Dr. Robert Mahal and Jr. in his brilliant book Invitation to a Journey says something a lot like this.

25:22.488 --> 25:28.996
He says that the inciting incident of all spiritual formation is confrontation.

25:30.298 --> 25:40.690
If indeed the work of God's formation in us is the process of conforming us to the image of Christ, obviously it's going to take place at points where we are not yet conformed to that image.

25:41.391 --> 25:47.218
This means that one of the first dynamics of holistic spiritual formation will be confrontation.

25:48.002 --> 25:56.890
So the way that we grow into the image of Jesus starts with the confrontational realization of where we are not currently like Jesus.

25:58.192 --> 26:08.321
It's the conviction of the Spirit in that stunning moment of clarity or it's when a pattern that you can't seem to curb by your own willpower is addressed by God.

26:08.782 --> 26:17.810
It's when new life circumstances and a new chapter of your life also bring about new awareness within you.

26:18.306 --> 26:39.301
like the newfound freedom that comes with going to college, or the newfound intimacy in a marriage, or the need of children in your home, or the boredom of retirement suddenly confronts me with how indulgent I am, or how selfish I am, how impatient I am, how discontent I am, how attached I am, confrontation.

26:40.523 --> 26:42.546
That's where spiritual formation starts.

26:43.266 --> 26:47.133
But we can respond to the Spirit's confrontation one of two ways.

26:47.193 --> 26:56.709
Being confronted by God doesn't effortlessly lead to depth because we get to decide whether that confrontation guides us to denial or to depth.

26:57.851 --> 27:06.706
Confronted, I can deny my need for formation by blaming it on my outside circumstances or blaming the other people who are involved or both.

27:07.394 --> 27:13.943
or I can deny my need for my own formation by just trying to fix my outer circumstances or fix the other people involved or both.

27:14.784 --> 27:30.345
Denial is the willful ignorance of my own need for formation because when life is confronting me, I don't deny the need, but I assume that I can deal with the need outside of me rather than inside of me.

27:31.466 --> 27:34.290
Depth is cultivated when life confronts me,

27:35.682 --> 27:37.344
Like there's a broken pattern in me.

27:38.445 --> 27:39.046
There's a rift.

27:39.106 --> 27:40.627
I can't seem to fix in my marriage.

27:40.647 --> 27:43.470
There's this theme that keeps coming up in my workplace.

27:43.490 --> 27:45.052
There's an issue in my parenting.

27:45.292 --> 27:48.636
There's an attachment I itch for every time it's taken away.

27:48.916 --> 27:54.082
And then I respond by looking within and saying, oh, okay, Jesus.

27:55.684 --> 27:56.485
Yeah, I see that.

27:58.006 --> 27:58.807
I confess it.

28:00.269 --> 28:01.330
And I ask for your help.

28:03.152 --> 28:05.234
And you know where Jesus will lead those?

28:05.634 --> 28:11.761
who when confronted choose depth, exactly where I thought I did not want to go.

28:13.182 --> 28:15.565
See, depth is the journey of incarnated prayer.

28:15.605 --> 28:22.592
It is letting Jesus lead me where I do not want to go to become who I want to be.

28:22.633 --> 28:25.596
And now we're back where we started.

28:27.418 --> 28:35.026
Several weeks ago, Morgan, who's an elder at our church and a business owner in our city and one of my very closest friends, Morgan was

28:35.106 --> 28:40.715
sitting with me, talking about this nudge he was feeling to meet God in the needs of his neighbors.

28:41.496 --> 28:53.314
But he was also confessing that that was going to require some real intention on his part, because just by nature of his life and his vocation, he tends to run in the social circles of the haves, not the have-nots.

28:53.394 --> 28:58.482
And so Morgan's explaining all this, and I just suggested, well, why don't you pray?

28:59.938 --> 29:09.492
Like rather than try to drum up God's invitation to you, why don't you just take this lung to God, name it to him and then see what he brings about.

29:10.153 --> 29:11.095
That was Tuesday.

29:11.155 --> 29:18.065
Morgan was over at my house for dinner that Friday and he was all wound up and excited and was like, Tyler, I've got to tell you what happened when I prayed.

29:19.307 --> 29:23.113
It turns out that the very next morning, Morgan's sitting on his porch Wednesday morning.

29:23.133 --> 29:29.362
This Bible open on his lap and a cup of coffee and he just prays, Lord, will you please walk me into one

29:29.442 --> 29:31.485
friendship with one neighbor in need.

29:33.108 --> 29:33.809
Why that prayer?

29:33.849 --> 29:38.257
Because that was where his resources and the needs of his neighbors overlapped.

29:39.058 --> 29:40.721
I can't do everything for everybody.

29:40.741 --> 29:47.012
I've got certain limitations, certain opportunities, but one friendship that I really dedicate myself to.

29:47.152 --> 29:49.095
I have capacity for that.

29:49.416 --> 29:50.858
I think God's equipped me for that.

29:52.000 --> 29:55.666
So he asked God for it, and then he's sitting there sipping coffee, reading scripture, and

29:56.386 --> 30:04.375
Just a few minutes later, this dude from DeShevel looking dude across the street just makes a beeline, walks right up to Morgan's porch and says, excuse me, sir.

30:05.176 --> 30:09.360
I'm living on the street right now, but I'm looking for work and I'm not on anything.

30:09.380 --> 30:10.602
I'm not trying to swindle you here.

30:10.622 --> 30:12.704
I just genuinely need help.

30:12.724 --> 30:15.848
Do you think you could help me find some work?

30:15.868 --> 30:25.298
And Morgan's like, are you an angel or a real person?

30:25.378 --> 30:34.876
Louie and Morgan go on to exchange numbers and then a few days later, Morgan's on a business call on one end of the city and Louie texts him from the other and says, hey, I need a ride to Northeast.

30:35.237 --> 30:37.802
Is there any chance that you could pick me up and help me out?

30:38.443 --> 30:39.826
That's how Morgan ends up.

30:39.906 --> 30:49.243
picking Louie up from underneath the highway overpass in the middle of the workday between appointments and then spends about an hour and a half in total getting him from here to there.

30:49.623 --> 30:51.527
The two of them talking the whole way.

30:51.587 --> 31:04.530
It was how prayer that began on Morgan's lips on the comfort of his porch led to prayer in Morgan's feet as Jesus through Louie led Morgan where he did not want to go.

31:05.890 --> 31:08.294
led Morgan to a confrontation with need.

31:08.694 --> 31:11.919
The need of his neighbor, sure, but his own need as well.

31:13.081 --> 31:16.326
Because you see, prayer is the exercise of anti-control.

31:17.728 --> 31:21.113
Some of us, we think prayer is how we exercise our agency.

31:21.173 --> 31:21.694
It's not.

31:22.395 --> 31:24.178
Prayer is how you exercise your surrender.

31:25.219 --> 31:28.524
It is an act of willing disordered, not greater order.

31:29.145 --> 31:34.834
Only by prayer does my neighbor actually become my neighbor and not just a violation of my autonomy.

31:35.714 --> 31:37.456
or an interruption to my order.

31:38.037 --> 31:42.403
Only by prayer does compassion even become possible.

31:42.423 --> 31:50.454
So weeks later, as Morgan shared with me, the beautiful mess that Jesus through Louis had made of all of his control and autonomy.

31:50.875 --> 32:02.290
He began to describe personal disordered attachments and affections that he had for certain badges of status and privilege that were all of the sudden just effortlessly peeling off of him.

32:03.650 --> 32:25.631
He was confronted by God through prayer, and he could have chosen denial, but instead he walked through the other door, the one marked depth, and he described the freedom that he had tried to discipline and practice into his life through these disordered attachments for so long, and then all of the sudden that freedom was just being given to him through the most unlikely of sources.

32:26.012 --> 32:32.338
Louis, the very person he thought he was supposed to bring freedom to,

32:33.378 --> 32:49.226
And as he described all of this to me, both of us just wept and wept because Jesus through Louie was leading Morgan where he thought he did not want to go to become who he knew he most wanted to be.

32:49.306 --> 32:53.874
And that is what it means to incarnate our prayers.

32:54.466 --> 33:09.050
It just means that just as God who is spirit took on flesh, so do my spirit-saturated quiet prayers of listening and speaking, that they're meant to take on flesh to become embodied in my hands and feet.

33:09.571 --> 33:19.026
An incarnated prayer will lead you exactly where the incarnation ultimately led Jesus, and that is to the cross, to die to yourself.

33:20.034 --> 33:27.283
to a confrontation with all of your disordered attachments, and your misplaced affections, and your false identities that are robbing you of life.

33:29.485 --> 33:32.109
And you can opt out of that process if you want.

33:33.210 --> 33:34.932
You can hold on to all those things.

33:34.972 --> 33:38.957
You can live in denial, or you can go where prayer is sending you.

33:39.237 --> 33:40.098
And that is to depth.

33:41.840 --> 33:43.723
As deep as a body, later in a tomb.

33:44.864 --> 33:47.487
And for those who choose depth, we know what's on the other side.

33:47.527 --> 33:48.348
It's resurrection.

33:49.209 --> 33:49.970
It's life.

33:50.946 --> 33:54.592
life in me and plenty of life to share with the world around me.

33:54.672 --> 34:00.300
That is incarnated prayer, letting Jesus lead me where I do not want to go to become who I want to be.

34:01.001 --> 34:03.826
Who in this room is being confronted by the Spirit of God right now?

34:09.875 --> 34:17.266
Just as I'm teaching, something in your life coming to mind,

34:21.026 --> 34:24.252
Have you confused prayer with agency, not surrender?

34:24.332 --> 34:28.960
Do you love your autonomy more than your neighbor?

34:32.286 --> 34:36.915
Are you asking Jesus to go with you where you want to lead him, not the other way around?

34:37.336 --> 34:39.660
Who's being confronted by the Spirit of God right now?

34:40.862 --> 34:43.026
Like a longing is waking up in you.

34:49.346 --> 34:59.470
that I want to be led by the rod and staff of the good shepherd, exactly where I'm not sure I want to go, because only he knows how to make me who I want to be.

35:00.633 --> 35:02.838
If that's you, if that's waking up and you eat, just stand.

35:02.878 --> 35:08.050
I just want to pray for you before we move on.

35:19.586 --> 35:20.948
How good shepherd lead us.

35:22.270 --> 35:22.751
Lead us.

35:24.493 --> 35:27.878
Green pastures and still waters and the value of the shadow of death.

35:27.918 --> 35:33.546
All of it, all of it is good as long as we know your presence with us.

35:35.769 --> 35:39.555
And so we surrender even the formation of our souls.

35:41.157 --> 35:44.722
And we say, God, if I knew how to make me whole, I would have done it by now.

35:48.290 --> 35:49.892
But I believe that you do Jesus.

35:52.695 --> 35:54.137
So will you take me to that place?

35:55.599 --> 35:56.360
In Jesus' name.

35:57.321 --> 35:57.641
Amen.

35:59.263 --> 36:09.035
So the practice for this teaching series is prayer and exercise that we're gonna engage this week as we gather around tables in our britishong communities is incarnated prayer.

36:09.115 --> 36:12.279
We're gonna learn the mechanics of praying with our hands and feet.

36:12.299 --> 36:17.746
Well, we've already been praying with our eyes, ears and lips, but for now I'll close here.

36:18.914 --> 36:20.417
Tyler, I love you.

36:20.457 --> 36:23.802
And I will always love you.

36:27.208 --> 36:30.454
But I'm not sure I like being around who you've most recently become.

36:31.536 --> 36:36.083
There I was at the pool on the first day of vacation all bent out of shape over a plastic fork.

36:37.546 --> 36:40.731
And when Kirsten said that to me, there was love in her eyes not anger.

36:40.851 --> 36:42.354
It was a confrontation.

36:44.066 --> 36:49.013
But it was one I knew the second I heard it was coming from the Spirit of God through my loving wife.

36:50.735 --> 36:56.583
You know, Jesus took one of his disciples on another walk after this long walk from Galilee to Jerusalem.

36:57.324 --> 36:57.905
It was Peter.

36:57.965 --> 37:02.551
After his resurrection, Jesus went and found him on a beach and took him on a walk.

37:02.631 --> 37:05.976
Peter had denied Jesus and that Jesus showed up to confront Peter.

37:06.437 --> 37:09.481
But when he confronted Peter, it was love in his eyes, not anger.

37:09.501 --> 37:13.266
It was a confrontation inviting him to greater depth.

37:13.986 --> 37:15.228
John 21, 18.

37:16.009 --> 37:20.236
Very truly, I tell you, when you were younger, you dressed yourself and went where you wanted.

37:20.616 --> 37:30.331
But when you are old, Jesus said to Peter, you will stretch out your hands and someone else will dress you and lead you where you do not want to go.

37:30.351 --> 37:31.653
That's how he said it.

37:32.895 --> 37:35.379
It's how he worded this loving confrontation.

37:35.419 --> 37:40.146
And some false part of Peter died as he let Jesus lead him where he didn't want to go.

37:41.538 --> 37:48.348
also that more of the fearfully and wonderfully made, God breathed and God knit part of Peter could live in this world.

37:49.810 --> 37:57.881
And following that moment at the pool on the first day of vacation, Jesus took me on a walk like that one, like the one he took Peter on.

37:57.921 --> 38:06.674
One where I'd lost some part of myself because somewhere along the way and all the well-intentioned yeses, I'd lost my laughter.

38:07.330 --> 38:08.912
my playfulness, my ease.

38:08.972 --> 38:12.457
And so I began to just pray this simple prayer every single day.

38:13.538 --> 38:18.144
Oh God, please, would you recover my silliness?

38:20.407 --> 38:25.554
I dropped it somewhere back there and I don't know how to retrace my steps to find it.

38:26.995 --> 38:28.838
And I didn't tell a soul about that prayer.

38:30.580 --> 38:32.082
For months and months, I prayed it.

38:32.102 --> 38:35.186
And then the first time I got to go back to New York

38:35.650 --> 38:37.172
see a really old friend.

38:37.332 --> 38:39.214
I was catching up with him over coffee.

38:39.254 --> 38:47.664
And as I was getting up to leave the coffee, he said, hey, man, if there's just one thing I could pray for you between now and whenever I get to see you again, what would it be?

38:47.684 --> 38:51.349
And I was like, man, to be honest, I've never told anyone this.

38:52.810 --> 38:56.555
But I pray every day that God would recover my silliness.

38:58.277 --> 38:59.378
So I guess it'd be that.

38:59.398 --> 39:02.482
And he was like, OK, got it.

39:03.138 --> 39:08.883
Just over a week ago, I got to see him again for the first time since then, and we had coffee again.

39:10.185 --> 39:15.990
And as I was getting up to leave, he said, hey, by the way, ever since I last saw you, I've been praying that thing about your silliness.

39:17.652 --> 39:18.412
How's that going?

39:18.452 --> 39:25.479
And I teared up when he asked me the question.

39:27.361 --> 39:33.106
And I said, it has been the kindest, slowest work of God.

39:34.722 --> 39:37.626
You see, my three-year-old Amos is obsessed with Nerf guns.

39:38.707 --> 39:41.130
And look, don't start judging me right now, okay?

39:41.230 --> 39:45.575
I don't think weapons of combat are good ideas for toys either, okay?

39:45.996 --> 39:47.958
I don't condone gun violence.

39:48.339 --> 39:55.367
I think my three-year-old's obsession with shooting his family members is absolutely morally and philosophically problematic.

39:56.609 --> 40:04.338
But his uncle Felix apparently disagrees and took the liberty of introducing my children

40:05.282 --> 40:07.444
to weaponry as a form of fun.

40:07.505 --> 40:14.753
And look, I'll be honest, I can't stand the little foam darts all over my house.

40:15.694 --> 40:30.851
And the way that Amos is always trying to shoot me while I'm doing normal household tasks and making them more difficult and his insistence on shooting them in the kitchen when we have a whole basement and blah, blah, blah, okay?

40:32.473 --> 40:33.554
Anyway, at some point,

40:34.338 --> 40:40.404
When I was asking God to recover my silliness, Jesus invited me to keep on praying that, but start praying it with my hands and feet.

40:42.326 --> 40:47.971
And it was then that I realized, you know, that I have a three-year-old son who is desperate to nerf battle me.

40:51.194 --> 40:54.297
And one day he's gonna grow up and he's gonna move out of our house.

40:56.379 --> 41:04.146
And on that day, I will long for someone to shoot me directly in the left pupil with a foam era.

41:06.914 --> 41:13.385
And so as far as it depends on me, I will not let the sun set on a single day.

41:14.867 --> 41:17.532
One my three-year-old wants to shoot me with a Nerf gun.

41:19.054 --> 41:30.173
That's how I ended up army crawling every evening on my hardwood kitchen floor, dodging darts in a battle for the ages that refuses to quit.

41:30.954 --> 41:33.138
Every single evening, when I get home,

41:33.346 --> 41:40.413
I hit the garage door and when Amos can hear it going up, I hear like his feet taking off running upstairs.

41:40.433 --> 41:45.358
And when I enter the house, he rips his shirt off and goes, ah!

41:45.378 --> 41:45.979
And it is on.

41:46.439 --> 41:49.743
And he is ready to storm behind enemy lines.

41:49.803 --> 41:55.749
And I'm ducking behind kitchen counters and crawling on my knees behind furniture in our home and everything like that.

41:55.809 --> 42:01.074
And then dying a dramatic slow, painful death each and every evening.

42:02.818 --> 42:05.161
And you know what, most days I don't feel like it.

42:06.823 --> 42:09.527
When I get home, I feel a lot like I did that day at the pool.

42:11.270 --> 42:16.537
Like I'm physically tired and emotionally drained and relationally empty and spiritually depleted.

42:18.019 --> 42:19.521
But you know what, I do it anyway.

42:19.561 --> 42:24.848
Because it's a way for me to pray with my hands and feet, what I started praying with my lips.

42:25.069 --> 42:29.074
And Jesus,

42:30.242 --> 42:40.196
Slowly but surely by the hand of my little three-year-old boy is leading me where I do not want to go to become who I most want to be.

42:40.236 --> 42:42.199
I'm laughing more.

42:42.239 --> 42:44.322
I'm living more lightly.

42:44.783 --> 42:47.046
I'm taking myself a lot less seriously.

42:47.066 --> 42:52.875
I'm much less preoccupied by the availability of plastic forks in my general vicinity.

42:53.616 --> 42:58.002
God is recovering my silliness, my playfulness.

42:58.370 --> 43:00.793
my ease, one Nerf dart at a time.

43:00.854 --> 43:11.028
The most formative and essential spiritual practice in my life the last three or four years is Nerf battling my youngest son.

43:11.990 --> 43:17.077
And that too, if you can bear to believe it, is incarnated prayer.

43:18.179 --> 43:18.900
Why don't we stand?

43:21.023 --> 43:23.346
Would you come Holy Spirit?

43:27.618 --> 43:31.442
Thanks for joining the Bridgestown family as we engage in this teaching series.

43:32.182 --> 43:38.108
To learn more about the life of our church and how you can get involved, visit bridgestown.church.com.

43:38.889 --> 43:46.976
If you're interested in contributing financially to Bridgestown Church and to our ministry, you can do that at bridgestown.church.gov.

43:47.737 --> 43:57.106
Wherever you're joining us from, we hope this resource blesses you and encourages you to be with Jesus, become like Jesus, and do what Jesus did.

